PROTECTING YOUR BUSINESS

With large amounts of cash on hand and often small staffs working, video lottery casinos can be viewed as easy targets for burglars and robbers. We encourage you to take steps to protect your business, employees and customers. Here are some tips: Conduct a Burglary Self-Assessment Test on your casino. Are all exterior entrances and exits well lit? Does your camera surveillance system have recording capabilities? Do you have a security alarm system that's monitored by local law enforcement or an alarm company? Instruct your employees to make note of suspicious people in the business or vehicles that are out of place after hours. Have your employees empty video lottery machines and the tills before leaving the casino at night. Implement a plan for what your employees should do to protect themselves and customers if confronted by a robber. Ensure ALL employees are aware of the plan. Burglaries and robberies are among the most difficult crimes to solve. If your casino is victimized, contact local law enforcement then submit a Video Lottery Burglary Report Form to the Lottery. Both Lottery Security and the Division of Criminal Investigation will use the information to track trends and identify weaknesses that burglars exploit for their crimes. Completed Video Lottery Burglary Report Forms can be mailed to: South Dakota Lottery Attn: Lottery Security 711 E. PROTECTING YOUR BUSINESS<\/h2>\r\nWith large amounts of cash on hand and often small staffs working, video lottery casinos can be viewed as easy targets for burglars and robbers. We encourage you to take steps to protect your business, employees and customers. Here are some tips:\r\n\r\nConduct a\u00a0Burglary Self-Assessment Test<\/a>\u00a0on your casino. Are all exterior entrances and exits well lit? Does your camera surveillance system have recording capabilities? Do you have a security alarm system that's monitored by local law enforcement or an alarm company?\r\n\r\nInstruct your employees to make note of suspicious people in the business or vehicles that are out of place after hours.\r\n\r\nHave your employees empty video lottery machines and the tills before leaving the casino at night.\r\n\r\nImplement a plan for what your employees should do to protect themselves and customers if confronted by a robber. Ensure ALL employees are aware of the plan.\r\n\r\nBurglaries and robberies are among the most difficult crimes to solve. If your casino is victimized, contact local law enforcement then submit a\u00a0Video Lottery Burglary Report Form<\/a>\u00a0to the Lottery. Both Lottery Security and the Division of Criminal Investigation will use the information to track trends and identify weaknesses that burglars exploit for their crimes.\r\n\r\nCompleted Video Lottery Burglary Report Forms can be mailed to:\r\n\r\nSouth Dakota Lottery\r\nAttn: Lottery Security\r\n711 E. Wells Avenue\r\nPierre, SD 57501-7107\r\n\r\nOr, email your completed form to: videolottery@state.sd.us<\/a>","_wysiwyg":"field_620e84f0afc08","section_padding_padding_top":"0","_section_padding_padding_top":"field_620ea24570e44","section_padding_padding_bottom":"1","_section_padding_padding_bottom":"field_620ea25570e45","section_padding":"","_section_padding":"field_620e9790b97d6"},"mode":"edit"},"attributesType":{"name":{"type":"string"},"data":{"type":"object"},"align":{"type":"string"},"mode":{"type":"string"},"anchor":{"type":"string"},"lock":{"type":"object"},"className":{"type":"string"},"metadata":{"type":"object"},"blockCommentId":{"type":"number"}},"dynamicContent":"

PRIZES OF $101 OR MORE

Prizes of $101 or more must be paid by the Lottery. You can claim your prize in person or by mail: Prizes from $101 to $5,000 may also be claimed through our mobile app! You may claim your prize in person by visiting one of our validation centers in Pierre, Rapid City or Sioux Falls.
  1. Sign the back of the ticket in the space provided;
  2. Fill out a claim form, available at your local lottery retailer. Or use the online Claim Form. Simply type in your information on the form, print it off, then sign and date it.
  3. Send the completed claim form and winning ticket to the Lottery at 711 E. Wells Avenue, Pierre, SD 57501.
  4. You should receive your prize money in 7-10 days.
  5. Please note that only prizes from $101 to $5,000 are eligible to receive payment through ACH transaction.
Any jackpot-winning ticket for Dakota Cash or Lotto America, top prize-winning ticket for Lucky for Life, or for the second prizes for Powerball and Mega Millions must be presented in person at a Lottery office. WON THE JACKPOT?

Congratulations! Our first advice is that you immediately sign the back of the ticket and put it in a safe place. We strongly encourage you to take your time and seek professional financial and legal advice. We also offer a Winner's Handbook with some tips to help you. When you're ready, give us a call to make arrangements to validate the ticket and claim your prize.

TAXES

Federal Law requires the Lottery to report winnings of more than $600 to the IRS and to withhold 24 percent of any claim of more than $5,000, effective Jan. 1, 2018.

If I win, can I remain anonymous?

Should a lottery prize winner choose to remain anonymous when claiming the prize, the South Dakota Lottery will honor that request. It should also be noted that the Lottery will release the name of the retailer that sold the winning ticket, game name and prize amount. The winning player’s personal information will never be shared for advertising or promotions unless the player opts into this on their claim form. However, if the Lottery receives an open records request for the winner’s information, we are obligated to provide the winner’s name, city, state of residence, game, and prize amount per SDCL 42-7A-50.1.

TIME LIMIT TO CLAIM PRIZE

Lotto prizes must be claimed within 180 days after the date of the drawing in which the prize was won. Scratch ticket prizes can be claimed up to 180 days after the announced end date of a game. View the Scratch Games page to see the list of all active games. If the game is not listed as an active game then it has expired and prizes can no longer be claimed. PRIZES OF $101 OR MORE<\/h2>\r\nPrizes of $101 or more must be paid by the Lottery. You can claim your prize in person or by mail: Prizes from $101 to $5,000 may also be claimed through our mobile app!<\/a>\r\n\r\nYou may claim your prize in person by visiting one of our validation centers in Pierre, Rapid City or Sioux Falls.\r\n
    \r\n \t
  1. Sign the back of the ticket in the space provided;<\/li>\r\n \t
  2. Fill out a claim form, available at your local lottery retailer. Or use the online Claim Form. Simply type in your information on the form, print it off, then sign and date it.<\/li>\r\n \t
  3. Send the completed claim form and winning ticket to the Lottery at 711 E. Wells Avenue, Pierre, SD 57501<\/span><\/a>.<\/li>\r\n \t
  4. You should receive your prize money in 7-10 days.<\/li>\r\n \t
  5. Please note that only prizes from $101 to $5,000 are eligible to receive payment through ACH transaction.<\/li>\r\n<\/ol>\r\nAny jackpot-winning ticket for Dakota Cash or Lotto America, top prize-winning ticket for Lucky for Life, or for the second prizes for Powerball and Mega Millions must be presented in person at a Lottery office<\/span><\/a>.     WON THE JACKPOT?<\/h2>\r\nCongratulations! Our first advice is that you immediately sign the back of the ticket and put it in a safe place. We strongly encourage you to take your time and seek professional financial and legal advice. We also offer a Winner's Handbook<\/a> with some tips to help you. When you're ready, give us a call to make arrangements to validate the ticket and claim your prize.\r\n

    TAXES<\/h2>\r\nFederal Law requires the Lottery to report winnings of more than $600 to the IRS and to withhold 24 percent of any claim of more than $5,000, effective Jan. 1, 2018.\r\n

    If I win, can I remain anonymous?<\/h2>\r\nShould a lottery prize winner choose to remain anonymous when claiming the prize, the South Dakota Lottery will honor that request. It should also be noted that the Lottery will release the name of the retailer that sold the winning ticket, game name and prize amount.\r\n\r\nThe winning player\u2019s personal information will never be shared for advertising or promotions unless the player opts into this on their claim form. However, if the Lottery receives an open records request for the winner\u2019s information, we are obligated to provide the winner\u2019s name, city, state of residence, game, and prize amount per SDCL 42-7A-50.1<\/a>.\r\n

    TIME LIMIT TO CLAIM PRIZE<\/h2>\r\nLotto prizes must be claimed within 180 days after the date of the drawing in which the prize was won.\r\n\r\nScratch ticket prizes can be claimed up to 180 days after the announced end date of a game. View the Scratch Games page<\/span><\/a> to see the list of all active games. If the game is not listed as an active game then it has expired and prizes can no longer be claimed.\r\n\r\nThe last day to claim a prize has been set for the active scratch games.","_wysiwyg":"field_620e84f0afc08","section_padding_padding_top":"0","_section_padding_padding_top":"field_620ea24570e44","section_padding_padding_bottom":"1","_section_padding_padding_bottom":"field_620ea25570e45","section_padding":"","_section_padding":"field_620e9790b97d6"},"mode":"edit"},"attributesType":{"name":{"type":"string"},"data":{"type":"object"},"align":{"type":"string"},"mode":{"type":"string"},"anchor":{"type":"string"},"lock":{"type":"object"},"className":{"type":"string"},"metadata":{"type":"object"},"blockCommentId":{"type":"number"}},"dynamicContent":"

How To Claim

You can begin your mobile claim in a few easy steps! Please see our video tutorial and contact the Lottery if you have any questions.
  • Open the SD Lottery mobile app on your device.
  • Make sure that you are logged into your Players Club account. Only Players Club members are eligible for mobile claims.
  • Select Scan Tickets. Make sure your device has granted camera permissions to the app.
  • If your ticket has a prize from $101 and $5,000, you can select the mobile claim option.
  • Complete your digital claim form. Please ensure that all information is accurate before submitting your claim.
  • Your payment should be processed within 4 businesses days. It's important to note that your first transaction may take up to 8 business days.
  • You can check the status of your claim on the app by clicking the Mobile Claims option from the main menu.
  • Sign the back of your winning ticket and hold onto it until the claim is complete.
  • Applicable documents such as your W2-G will be emailed to you.
 

Don't have our mobile app? Download it today!

Frequently Asked Questions

 
What tickets are eligible for mobile claims?
Instant and lotto tickets with prizes from $101 and $5,000 are eligible for mobile claims.
When will I receive my prize?
Most claims are completed within 4 business days. Your first mobile claim may take 8 business days.
What if I receive an error message after submitting my claim?
This error may be due to your authentication credentials expiring. Please log out then back in to your Players Club account and submit the claim again. We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause.
How are multi draw lotto tickets processed?
If you have a multi draw ticket with a prize eligible for a mobile claim, you must complete the mobile claim after all draws on the ticket have been completed.
What if I make an error on my claim form?
If there is an error on your claim form, Lottery staff will reach out to determine next steps. This may result in your prize being delivered via mail. Please make sure to check the summary screen to ensure that all of your information is correct.
What if my bank account number isn't long enough?
If your bank account number does not meet the character requirements in the mobile app, enter zeroes before your bank account number.
Can I learn more about claiming Lottery prizes?
You can learn more about the prize claim process by visiting https://lottery.sd.gov/claim-your-prize/.

How To Claim<\/h2>\r\nYou can begin your mobile claim in a few easy steps! Please see our video tutorial and contact the Lottery if you have any questions.\r\n
    \r\n \t
  • Open the SD Lottery mobile app on your device.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Make sure that you are logged into your Players Club account. Only Players Club members are eligible for mobile claims.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Select Scan Tickets. Make sure your device has granted camera permissions to the app.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • If your ticket has a prize from $101 and $5,000, you can select the mobile claim option.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Complete your digital claim form. Please ensure that all information is accurate before submitting your claim.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Your payment should be processed within 4 businesses days. It's important to note that your first transaction may take up to 8 business days.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • You can check the status of your claim on the app by clicking the Mobile Claims option from the main menu.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Sign the back of your winning ticket and hold onto it until the claim is complete.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Applicable documents such as your W2-G will be emailed to you.<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n \r\n

    Frequently Asked Questions<\/span><\/h2>\r\n \r\n
    What tickets are eligible for mobile claims?<\/h5>\r\nInstant and lotto tickets with prizes from $101 and $5,000 are eligible for mobile claims.\r\n
    When will I receive my prize?<\/h5>\r\nMost claims are completed within 4 business days. Your first mobile claim may take 8 business days.\r\n
    What if I receive an error message after submitting my claim?<\/h5>\r\nThis error may be due to your authentication credentials expiring. Please log out then back in to your Players Club account and submit the claim again. We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause.\r\n
    How are multi draw lotto tickets processed?<\/h5>\r\nIf you have a multi draw ticket with a prize eligible for a mobile claim, you must complete the mobile claim after all draws on the ticket have been completed.\r\n
    What if I make an error on my claim form?<\/h5>\r\nIf there is an error on your claim form, Lottery staff will reach out to determine next steps. This may result in your prize being delivered via mail. Please make sure to check the summary screen to ensure that all of your information is correct.\r\n
    What if my bank account number isn't long enough?<\/h5>\r\nIf your bank account number does not meet the character requirements in the mobile app, enter zeroes before<\/strong> your bank account number.\r\n
    Can I learn more about claiming Lottery prizes?<\/h5>\r\nYou can learn more about the prize claim process by visiting https:\/\/lottery.sd.gov\/claim-your-prize\/.\r\n

South Dakota Lottery Commission is a five-member board appointed by the Governor. The Commission establishes policy for and advises on operation of the South Dakota Lottery, including approval of any major procurement. Members are appointed by the Governor and confirmed by the State Senate. Each commissioner's term is three years, and a chairman is chosen annually at the first meeting of the fiscal year. The commission meets at least once each quarter. Additional meetings may be called by the chair upon request of the Executive Director or any three commission members.

Tips to Play Responsibly

  • Playing responsibly means having a plan, a budget and an awareness of when playing is no longer about just having fun. Here are some tips to help you keep the fun good.
  • Play for fun and entertainment.
  • Understand that winning and losing are both part of gambling.
  • Never borrow money to gamble.
  • Never gamble to win back losses.
  • Don’t let gambling interfere with family, friends or work.
  • Only spend what you can afford to lose.
  • Use your entertainment budget to play — not money needed for daily living expenses.
  • Set a spending limit. Once you reach your limit, stop playing.

Tips to Play Responsibly

  • Playing responsibly means having a plan, a budget and an awareness of when playing is no longer about just having fun. Here are some tips to help you keep the fun good.
  • Play for fun and entertainment.
  • Understand that winning and losing are both part of gambling.
  • Never borrow money to gamble.
  • Never gamble to win back losses.
  • Don’t let gambling interfere with family, friends or work.
  • Only spend what you can afford to lose.
  • Use your entertainment budget to play — not money needed for daily living expenses.
  • Set a spending limit. Once you reach your limit, stop playing.

Warning Signs of Problem Gambling*

  • Preoccupied with gambling and unable to stop.
  • Bragging about gambling, exaggerating wins and minimizing losses.
  • Restless and irritable when not gambling.
  • Gambling to win back what’s been lost.
  • Borrowing money for gambling.
  • Lying to hide time spent gambling or unpaid debts.
  • Frequent unexplained absences.
  • Losing work time because of gambling.
  • Jeopardizing a significant relationship or job by gambling.

How to Reach Out to a Friend or Relative*

  • Find a comfortable place to talk where you won’t be disturbed.
  • Keep it simple and straightforward.
  • Tell the person you care about them and you’re concerned about how they are acting.
  • Tell the person exactly what they’ve done that concerns you.
  • Tell the person how their behavior is affecting other people and be specific.
  • Be clear about what you expect (“I want you to talk to someone about your gambling.”) and what they can expect from you (“I won’t cover for you anymore.”).
  • After you’ve told the person what you’ve seen and how you feel, allow them to respond. Listen with a nonjudgmental attitude.
  • Let the person know you’re willing to help, but don’t try to counsel them yourself.
  • Give the person information, not advice. Encourage them to call a problem gambling helpline.
  *Adapted from materials provided by the National Council on Problem Gambling.

Youth Gambling Facts

  • A large number of young people report their first gambling experience occurs around 9 to 11 years of age.
  • Lottery scratch tickets have been shown to present a possible gateway to other gambling activities.
  • Approximately 80% of high school-aged adolescents report having gambled for money during the past year.
  • Two to four percent of adolescents presently have a problem with gambling. To put it into perspective, adult gambling disorder prevalence rates are about one to two percent of the population.
  • Some adults report giving lottery tickets to children as gifts during the holiday season. If we can raise awareness and education on the risks of giving lottery products to children, we can do our part in minimizing potential harm.
A problem gambler doesn’t necessarily need to “hit bottom” to decide to get help. If someone you know is gambling for more than fun, they may have a problem. Talking to them can seem scary, but they need you to have courage. If you’re the spouse or family member of a problem gambler, it’s important for you to take care of yourself and realize that you’re not responsible for the gambler’s behavior. Even if your loved one isn’t ready or willing to get help, you may want to call a problem gambling helpline. Problem gambling is not a bad habit or a moral weakness. It’s a serious condition, but with treatment, problem gamblers can put the game in perspective and make decisions to improve their lives and Tips to Play Responsibly<\/h2>\r\n
    \r\n \t
  • Playing responsibly means having a plan, a budget and an awareness of when playing is no longer about just having fun. Here are some tips to help you keep the fun good.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Play for fun and entertainment.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Understand that winning and losing are both part of gambling.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Never borrow money to gamble.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Never gamble to win back losses.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Don\u2019t let gambling interfere with family, friends or work.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Only spend what you can afford to lose.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Use your entertainment budget to play \u2014 not money needed for daily living expenses.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • Set a spending limit.     Warning Signs of Problem Gambling*<\/h3>\r\n
      \r\n \t
    • Preoccupied with gambling and unable to stop.<\/li>\r\n \t
    • Bragging about gambling, exaggerating wins and minimizing losses.<\/li>\r\n \t
    • Restless and irritable when not gambling.<\/li>\r\n \t
    • Gambling to win back what\u2019s been lost.<\/li>\r\n \t
    • Borrowing money for gambling.<\/li>\r\n \t
    • Lying to hide time spent gambling or unpaid debts.<\/li>\r\n \t
    • Frequent unexplained absences.<\/li>\r\n \t
    • Losing work time because of gambling.<\/li>\r\n \t
    • Jeopardizing a significant relationship or job by gambling.<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>","_sides_1_multiple_content_0_content":"field_61eb1513ebc23_field_61eaf171c170d","sides_1_multiple_content_0_buttons":"","_sides_1_multiple_content_0_buttons":"field_61eb1513ebc23_field_61eaeedd176cd","sides_1_multiple_content_0_content_alignment":"left","_sides_1_multiple_content_0_content_alignment":"field_61eb1513ebc23_field_61eaf131c170c","sides_1_multiple_content":1,"_sides_1_multiple_content":"field_61eaf3b9dad06","sides":["image","content"],"_sides":"field_61eaf3a2dad05","mobile_reverse":"0","_mobile_reverse":"field_61eb191980e7f","background_color":"white","_background_color":"field_61eaf2edc1713","block_settings":"","_block_settings":"field_61eb154debc24"},"mode":"edit"},"attributesType":{"name":{"type":"string"},"data":{"type":"object"},"align":{"type":"string"},"mode":{"type":"string"},"anchor":{"type":"string"},"lock":{"type":"object"},"className":{"type":"string"},"metadata":{"type":"object"},"blockCommentId":{"type":"number"}},"dynamicContent":"

      How to Reach Out to a Friend or Relative*<\/h3>\r\n
        \r\n \t
      • Find a comfortable place to talk where you won\u2019t be disturbed.<\/li>\r\n \t
      • Keep it simple and straightforward.<\/li>\r\n \t
      • Tell the person you care about them and you\u2019re concerned about how they are acting.<\/li>\r\n \t
      • Tell the person exactly what they\u2019ve done that concerns you.<\/li>\r\n \t
      • Tell the person how their behavior is affecting other people and be specific.<\/li>\r\n \t
      • Be clear about what you expect (\u201cI want you to talk to someone about your gambling.\u201d) and what they can expect from you (\u201cI won\u2019t cover for you anymore.\u201d).<\/li>\r\n \t
      • After you\u2019ve told the person what you\u2019ve seen and how you feel, allow them to respond. Listen with a nonjudgmental attitude.<\/li>\r\n \t
      • Let the person know you\u2019re willing to help, but don\u2019t try to counsel them yourself.<\/li>\r\n \t
      • Give the person information, not advice. Encourage them to call a problem gambling helpline.<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\n \r\n\r\n*Adapted from materials provided by the National Council on Problem Gambling.\r\n

        Youth Gambling Facts<\/h3>\r\n
          \r\n \t
        • A large number of young people report their first gambling experience occurs around 9 to 11 years of age.<\/li>\r\n \t
        • Lottery scratch tickets have been shown to present a possible gateway to other gambling activities.<\/li>\r\n \t
        • Approximately 80% of high school-aged adolescents report having gambled for money during the past year.<\/li>\r\n \t
        • Two to four percent of adolescents presently have a problem with gambling. To put it into perspective, adult gambling disorder prevalence rates are about one to two percent of the population.<\/li>\r\n \t
        • Some adults report giving lottery tickets to children as gifts during the holiday season. If we can raise awareness and education on the risks of giving lottery products to children, we can do our part in minimizing potential harm.<\/li>\r\n<\/ul>\r\nA problem gambler doesn\u2019t necessarily need to \u201chit bottom\u201d to decide to get help. If someone you know is gambling for more than fun, they may have a problem. Talking to them can seem scary, but they need you to have courage.\r\n\r\nIf you\u2019re the spouse or family member of a problem gambler, it\u2019s important for you to take care of yourself and realize that you\u2019re not responsible for the gambler\u2019s behavior. Even if your loved one isn\u2019t ready or willing to get help, you may want to call a problem gambling helpline.\r\n\r\nProblem gambling is not a bad habit or a moral weakness. It\u2019s a serious condition, but with treatment, problem gamblers can put the game in perspective and make decisions to improve their lives and yours.","_wysiwyg":"field_620e84f0afc08","section_padding_padding_top":"1","_section_padding_padding_top":"field_620ea24570e44","section_padding_padding_bottom":"1","_section_padding_padding_bottom":"field_620ea25570e45","section_padding":"","_section_padding":"field_620e9790b97d6"},"mode":"preview"},"attributesType":{"name":{"type":"string"},"data":{"type":"object"},"align":{"type":"string"},"mode":{"type":"string"},"anchor":{"type":"string"},"lock":{"type":"object"},"className":{"type":"string"},"metadata":{"type":"object"},"blockCommentId":{"type":"number"}},"dynamicContent":"

Prizes of $100 or Less

Sign the back of your ticket and present it to your local lottery retailer.

Prizes of $101 or More

These must be paid by the Lottery. You can claim your prize by mail:
  • Sign the back of the ticket in the space provided.
  • Fill out a claim form, available at your local lottery retailer. Or use the online Claim Form. Simply type in your information, print it off, sign and date it.
  • Send the completed claim form and winning ticket to the Lottery at 711 E Wells Ave., Pierre, SD 57501.
  • You should receive your prize money in 7-10 days.

Where The Money Goes

It’s the question we get most often... where does the money go? The simple answer is to South Dakota and South Dakotans. The more detailed answers about how it comes in, where it goes and what it benefits are below. The South Dakota Lottery is run like any other business. We take in revenue, we account for expenses, and whatever is left over is our net income. General Fund

The General Fund is the state government’s general spending account and supports public and higher education, programs like Medicaid and Temporary Assistance to Families in Need, human services facilities and the corrections and court systems. The state Bureau of Finance & Management provides a summary of General Fund receipts and expenditures for the current state fiscal year in its Budget in Brief document.

Capital Construction Fund

The Capital Construction Fund is a temporary stop for monies destined for other state funds:
  • 64% is sent to the Water & Environment Fund. This fund is used for rural water system development; to provide loans and grants to local communities for drinking water and wastewater improvement projects; recycling, solid waste disposal and waste tire projects; and regional landfills. More information on natural resource development projects is available from the Dept. of Agriculture & Natural Resources.
  • 36% is sent to the State Highway Fund. This fund is currently used for construction and maintenance of state highways and bridges and for public transportation. More information about the state highway system and public transportation is available from the Dept. of Transportation.
A portion of the Capital Construction Fund was previously sent to the Public and Special Transportation Assistance Fund.","_wysiwyg":"field_620e84f0afc08","section_padding_padding_top":"0","_section_padding_padding_top":"field_620ea24570e44","section_padding_padding_bottom":"1","_section_padding_padding_bottom":"field_620ea25570e45","section_padding":"","_section_padding":"field_620e9790b97d6"},"mode":"edit"},"innerBlocks":[]},{"name":"acf/cta-banner","attributes":{"name":"acf/cta-banner","data":{"headline_group_heading_level":"h3","_headline_group_heading_level":"field_61eaefed176d8","headline_group_headline":"Lottery Revenue","_headline_group_headline":"field_61eaefe5176d7","headline_group_headline_color":"default","_headline_group_headline_color":"field_61f3718846b13","headline_group":"","_headline_group":"field_61eaeebc176cb","content":"Each year, the South Dakota Lottery’s Annual Report details our progress in generating revenue from lotto, scratch and video lottery, and recounts the successes and advancements over the past year that will strengthen and enhance the Lottery in the future.

Video Lottery

Revenue generated by video lottery play is called Net Machine Income (NMI). NMI is calculated as cash put into the machines minus prizes cashed out (cash in – prizes out = NMI). The state currently receives 50% of NMI. The private machine owners (license operators) receive the other 50%. As of July 1, 2015, the state’s share of NMI is transferred to the state General Fund (49.5% of NMI). A small amount is kept by the Lottery for operation costs (0.5% of NMI). As of FY21, the state’s share of net machine income has generated $1.16 billion for the General Fund. From FY1997 to FY2015, the state’s share of NMI went to the Property Tax Reduction Fund. Revenue from video lottery play raised more than $1.92 billion for the Property Tax Reduction Fund through FY2015. General Fund<\/h3>\r\nThe General Fund is the state government\u2019s general spending account and supports public and higher education, programs like Medicaid and Temporary Assistance to Families in Need, human services facilities and the corrections and court systems.\r\n\r\nThe state Bureau of Finance & Management provides a summary of General Fund receipts and expenditures for the current state fiscal year in its Budget in Brief document.\r\n

Capital Construction Fund<\/h3>\r\nThe Capital Construction Fund is a temporary stop for monies destined for other state funds:\r\n
    \r\n \t
  • 64% is sent to the Water & Environment Fund. This fund is used for rural water system development; to provide loans and grants to local communities for drinking water and wastewater improvement projects; recycling, solid waste disposal and waste tire projects; and regional landfills. More information on natural resource development projects is available from the Dept. of Agriculture & Natural Resources.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • 36% is sent to the State Highway Fund. This fund is currently used for construction and maintenance of state highways and bridges and for public transportation.       Video Lottery<\/h3>\r\nRevenue generated by video lottery play is called Net Machine Income (NMI). NMI is calculated as cash put into the machines minus prizes cashed out (cash in \u2013 prizes out = NMI). The state currently receives 50% of NMI. The private machine owners (license operators) receive the other 50%.\r\n\r\nAs of July 1, 2015, the state\u2019s share of NMI is transferred to the state General Fund (49.5% of NMI). A small amount is kept by the Lottery for operation costs (0.5% of NMI). As of FY21, the state\u2019s share of net machine income has generated $1.16 billion for the General Fund.\r\n\r\nFrom FY1997 to FY2015, the state\u2019s share of NMI went to the Property Tax Reduction Fund. Revenue from video lottery play raised more than $1.92 billion for the Property Tax Reduction Fund through FY2015. Prizes of $100 or Less

Sign the back of your ticket and present it to your local lottery retailer.

Prizes of $101 or More

These must be paid by the Lottery. You can claim your prize by mail:
  • Sign the back of the ticket in the space provided.
  • Fill out a claim form, available at your local lottery retailer. Or use the online Claim Form. Simply type in your information, print it off, sign and date it.
  • Send the completed claim form and winning ticket to the Lottery at 711 E Wells Ave., Pierre, SD 57501.
  • You should receive your prize money in 7-10 days.

  • You should receive your prize money in 7-10 days.

Prizes of $100 or Less

Sign the back of your ticket and present it to your local lottery retailer.

Prizes of $101 or More

These must be paid by the Lottery. You can claim your prize by mail:
  • Sign the back of the ticket in the space provided.
  • Fill out a claim form, available at your local lottery retailer. Or use the online Claim Form. Simply type in your information, print it off, sign and date it.
  • Send the completed claim form and winning ticket to the Lottery at 711 E Wells Ave., Pierre, SD 57501.
  • You should receive your prize money in 7-10 days.

MOBILE CASHING IS HERE!

You may now securely and conveniently claim your prizes from $101 to $5,000 through the South Dakota Lottery's mobile app. Simply scan your instant or lotto tickets on the app to begin your claim via ACH transaction! To get started scan your winning scratch or lotto ticket from our app and complete your digital claim form. Your first mobile claim should be processed within 8 business days and future claims within 4 business days!

Prizes of $100 or Less

Sign the back of your ticket and present it to your local lottery retailer.

Prizes of $101 or More

These must be paid by the Lottery. You can claim your prize by mail:
  • Sign the back of the ticket in the space provided.
  • Fill out a claim form, available at your local lottery retailer. Or use the online Claim Form. Simply type in your information, print it off, sign and date it.
  • Send the completed claim form and winning ticket to the Lottery at 711 E Wells Ave., Pierre, SD 57501.
  • You should receive your prize money in 7-10 days.
","_tabs_2_tab_content_0_content":"field_62033cf4063b3","tabs_2_tab_content_1_content":"
  • You may also claim your prize in person by visiting one of our validation centers in Pierre, Rapid City or Sioux Falls.
  • Any jackpot-winning ticket or the second prizes for Mega Millions must be presented in person at a Lottery office. A jackpot-winning Mega Millions ticket must be presented in person at the Lottery office in Pierre at 711 E Wells Ave., Pierre, SD 57501.
  • You have 180 days from the winning draw date to claim your prize.

MOBILE CASHING IS HERE!<\/h4>\r\nYou may now securely and conveniently claim your prizes from $101 to $5,000 through the South Dakota Lottery's mobile app. Simply scan your instant or lotto tickets on the app to begin your claim via ACH transaction! To get started scan your winning scratch or lotto ticket from our app and complete your digital claim form. Your first mobile claim should be processed within 8 business days and future claims within 4 business days!\r\n

Prizes of $100 or Less<\/h4>\r\nSign the back of your ticket and present it to your local lottery retailer.\r\n

Prizes of $101 or More<\/h4>\r\nThese must be paid by the Lottery. You can claim your prize by mail:\r\n

  • Send the completed claim form and winning ticket to the Lottery at 711 E Wells Ave., Pierre, SD 57501<\/span><\/a>.<\/li>\r\n \t
  • You should receive your prize money in 7-10 days.<\/li>\r\n \t

Prizes of $100 or Less

Sign the back of your ticket and present it to your local lottery retailer.

Prizes of $101 or More

These must be paid by the Lottery. You can claim your prize by mail:
  • Sign the back of the ticket in the space provided.
  • Fill out a claim form, available at your local lottery retailer. Or use the online Claim Form. Simply type in your information, print it off, sign and date it.
  • Send the completed claim form and winning ticket to the Lottery at 711 E Wells Ave., Pierre, SD 57501.
  • You should receive your prize money in 7-10 days.

privacy, confidence, and trust of individuals who visit State of South Dakota websites are important to us. No personal information is collected unless provided voluntarily by an individual while participating in an online activity that requests the information. The State only collects the personal information necessary to provide the information or services requested by an individual. "Personal information" refers to any information relating to an identified or identifiable individual who is the subject of the information. This is the same information that an individual might provide when visiting a government office and includes such items as an individual's name, address, or phone number. We also collect information to help us understand how people are using state government websites so we can continually improve our services. The information collected is not associated with any specific individual and no attempt is made to profile individuals who browse state government websites. The State uses the collected information to respond appropriately to requests. E-mail or other informational requests sent to the State website may be maintained or forwarded to the appropriate agency in order to respond to the request. Survey information is used for the intended purpose of the survey. Informational records needed to support State functions are retained, managed, and accessible in record-keeping or filing systems in accordance with the State's Public Records Commission. Records transmitted to this site will be identified, managed, protected, and retained as long as they are needed to meet historical, administrative, fiscal, or legal requirements. The State of South Dakota is committed to the security of the information that is either available from or collected by state agency websites. The State continues to safeguard the integrity of its information, technology and computing infrastructure, including but not limited to: authentication, monitoring, auditing and encryption. Cookies, Web Beacons, and Similar Technologies This website uses cookies and other similar technologies, which are automatically generated, sent to your browser, and stored on your hard drive, to record information about how and when you use the website.  These cookies and other similar technologies identify a web browser on a specific computer or device and reveal certain non-personally identifiable information such as browser type, language, time zone, and operating system.  The cookies and other similar technologies used by this website do not identify you personally, but allow you to remain anonymous.  This website may still be used with cookies disabled, but some website functionality may be impaired. This website may also use web beacons or pixel tags and other similar technologies, which are not placed on your computer, but are instead embedded on certain pages of the website or in emails.  When you visit a page or read an email with a pixel tag, web beacon, or other similar technology, a generic notice of your interaction is generated. Non-personally identifiable information collected through this website may be used in aggregate for statistical purposes, and some of our analytics and digital marketing tools may combine the non-personally identifiable information collected from the website with non-personally identifiable information gathered from you through other websites for target advertising, remarketing, retargeting, or tracking referral purposes.  Third-party vendors like Google and Facebook use cookies, web beacons, and similar storage technologies to: (i) serve advertisements to you based on past visits to this website; (ii) to collect or receive information from this website and elsewhere on the Internet and use that information to provide measurement services and target advertisements; and (iii) show our advertisements to you on websites and apps across the Internet.  Your use of other websites and apps across the Internet is governed by the privacy policies of those websites and apps. All non-personally identifiable information we gather using cookies, pixel tags, web beacons, server logs, or other similar technologies are used as described in this privacy policy.  For information on how to opt-out of having cookies, web beacons, and other similar technologies used on your web browser, please see the “Opting Out of Cookies, Web Beacons, and Similar Technologies” section of this policy. Opting Out of Cookies, Web Beacons, and Similar Technologies You can manage cookie preferences and opt out of having cookies and other similar collection technologies used by adjusting the settings on your web browser.  If you do not want cookies stored on your computer, you can change the settings on your browser to notify you when a cookie is about to be saved or block cookies entirely.  How to access these settings, which settings are available, and how to turn on these settings varies by browser type, and we encourage you to further investigate your browser’s privacy settings if you wish to opt out or adjust these settings in any way.  If you choose to decline or block cookies, you may not be able to fully utilize all of the interactive features of the website. You can opt out of a third-party vendor's use of cookies, web beacons, and similar technologies by visiting the Network Advertising Initiative opt-out page, or learn more about your choices for limiting or disabling these tools by visiting http://www.aboutads.info/choices and http://www.youronlinechoices.eu/. You cannot decline web beacons; however, setting your browser to decline cookies or to prompt you for a response, or installing an ad-blocker, may keep web beacons from tracking your
